When I started to look, I was forced to confront my own ignorance. 
For decades, linguistics has had an ongoing debate about what models of language, like the Transformer, can reasonably be used for.
Sociologists, historians, and librarians have been navigating the ethics and challenges of data collected from, or left behind by humans also for decades.
Data availability and the process through which that data was collected would influence both the types of research that were possible and the systems that were built.

It's perhaps inexcusable that AI researchers are mostly brought up without ready exposure to prior work in these other disciplines.
It's perhaps an excuse to say that our field had just undergone a revolution when so many researchers have had underlying goals of understanding or recreating human cognition since the beginnings of AI as a discipline.
But somehow, the right people were not yet in touch, and through the work of many, the last few years have seen people across disciplines slowly meeting each other and translating their disciplines for each other.

And part of that is right. 
There are so many interesting questions to think about for each discipline.
There must be a compelling reason to think about a specific question.
Advances in technology makes particular questions more compelling: driverless cars revitalized the trolley problem, CRISPER ignited discussion about human evolution and meddling of science, and the previous age of AI saw discussion about [todo].
Society drives technology: the need for algorithmic decision making to perform just as well on marginalized groups as the majority group spurs research on algorithmic changes and changes to data collection procedures,
the desire for machines to fail in similar ways to humans selects particular technical solutions over others,
and 
People's time and attention are limited and we re-prioritize as we gather more information. 

Feel free to tell me that I've accepted the status quo too much.
I certainty used to feel that  the way things were was very wrong.

