In the example I've given of my work, technology and human desires go hand in hand. Human desires for automation or privacy influence the open questions and changes the way technology is designed. 
I'm heartened by the "sure, but" line of questioning because it introduces new technical challenges to be resolved. 
This is not a novel thought to any designer. But the actual practice of invoking both "yes, and" and "sure, but" is where I find myself caught in a loop.

It's very easy to flit between the two with half baked thoughts leading into each other. But you need to give yourself enough pause to explore an idea fully regardless of if it's a "yes, and" or "sure, but" thought.

