Humans are ceaselessly resourceful. But the best restaurants source the best ingredients, because while you can overcome, why should we expend energy overcoming instead of thriving?

Every innovation in human communication changes human communication: spoken language, Written language, mail, and email. Today, whether people type on their phone, use a computer, or use the swipe keyboard on a phone changes the way they use language^[cite]. 

Am I just trying to justify what is impossible to justify?
Is it completely morally corrupt?

Like every little girl, I used to dream of a robot assistant that would hand me the color of paint I wanted to use before I had completed my thought. 
I imagined it following me around, prompting me with little todos and advice.
Somehow, coming from my robotic assistant that felt desirable, but coming from my mother, less so

Later the phrase "slight of hand" seemed extremely relevant. 

And then I would respond with how I wasn't sure that adding technology was the right answer to that problem, since it seemed like it was a social problem, or that to get the technology right, you would need to know an awful lot about the social context the technology would be operating in. 

I spent two years only seeing the potential dangers. 
Around me, "yes, and"s swirled.

I had a love/hate relationship with planning the meta, frequently feeling like I was spending too much time designing courses of action and not enough executing on it.

